Correlations of age and sex with body proportions in physically-active adults

Data

We are using the Body Measurements dataset, bdims, which is a dataset of skeletal, muscle and other body part girth and diameter measurements, along with age, weight, height and sex. The data include 507 physically active individuals, comprised of 247 men and 260 women. We chose this dataset out of interest for human health and body proportions, as most of us are pre-health students.

Research questions

  1. Is there a difference between the bicep girth to thigh girth ratios in male versus female populations?

Hypothesis: We hypothesize that the ratio of bicep girth to thigh girth is higher for male than female populations.

  1. Is there a statistically significant difference in shoulder girth between men and women of the same weight?

Hypothesis: We hypothesize that when comparing men and women of the same weight, there will be a difference in average shoulder girth, with men having a larger average shoulder girth than females.

  1. Is there a difference in the proportion of women with a waist girth above 39in between early adult and middle adult age populations?

Hypothesis: We hypothesize that the middle adult age women will have a higher proportion of waist girths above 39in than early adult women.

Resources

  1. Janssen, I., & Heymsfield, S. B. (2016, September 27). Skeletal muscle mass and distribution in 468 men and women aged 18–88 yr. Retrieved March 2, 2020, from https://www.researchgate.net/publication/306150258_Skeletal_muscle_mass_and_distribution_in_468_men_and_women_aged_18-88_yr

This article describes the correlation between upper and lower body muscle mass between men and women from ages 18-88 years old. The information we retrieved from this article helped us arrive at our first question to analyze the differences in upper and lower body girth, specifically thighs and biceps. We are curious to see if there is a correlation between these two muscle groups or not and will use our data to explore the relationship between the two.

  1. Miller, A. E., MacDougall, J. D., Tarnopolsky, M. A., & Sale, D. G. (1993). Gender differences in strength and muscle fiber characteristics. Retrieved March 2, 2020, from https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8477683

This article displays the differences in strength between men and women. At first, this peaked our interest in the natural differences between men and women and influenced our research questions. The differences displayed that men are generally stronger than women. We wanted to see if there is a correlation in our data that confirms or denies this relationship which led to the creation of our research questions.

  1. Boundless. (n.d.). Boundless Psychology. Retrieved from https://courses.lumenlearning.com/boundless-psychology/chapter/early-and-middle-adulthood/

This article describes the discreet stages of adulthood and the age cutoffs for each. This helped us develop our third research question, which explores a physical change, waist girth, across the different age groups. The article describes many psychological differences that occur in different stages of adult hood, and we will explore if there are distinct physical physique differences as well. Early adult aged women are from ages 20-40, and middle adult aged women are from ages 40-65.

Exploratory data analysis

QUESTION 1: We hypothesized that the proportion of bicep girth to thigh girth would be the same in men and women. Our analyses included 260 females and 247 males. The scatter plot shows that as thigh girth increases, so does bicep girth for both men and women. Although there were a few outliers in both categories and males had larger biceps, once we plotted the data on a scatter plot, a more or less linear relationship was revealed. This preliminary scatterplot showed us that we could easily examine bicep and thigh girth through a basic ratio instead of needing to use logarithms or other methods. As for the ratios of bicep girth to thigh girth, the box plots both suggest a normal distributions due to the few outliers and the whiskers not extending far too out on either side for both male and females. The spread of both plots are similar, with the IQR for males being 0.054, and that for females being 0.039. Males tend to have a slightly higher ratio for bicep girth to thigh girth, showed by the center of the box plot at the median for males at 0.606, while the box plot is centered at the median of 0.489 for females. Males tend to have a larger bicep girth to thigh girth ratio and based off the box plot, and this can be attributed to the slightly larger bicep girth of males compared to females but more or less similar thigh girth between male and female, which is visible in the preliminary scatter plot. In conclusion, the relationship between thigh girth and bicep girth between men and women is different, with that of males being larger than that of females. Thus, this preliminary EDA is is in support of our hypothesis that the ratio is the same between men and women.

sex_bdims <- bdims %>%
  mutate(sex_categorical = ifelse(sex < 0.5, "female", "male"))
p = sex_bdims %>%
ggplot( aes(x=thi_gi, y=bic_gi, group=sex_categorical, color=sex_categorical)) +
    geom_point() +
      geom_smooth(aes(color = sex_categorical), method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  xlab('Thigh Girth') +
  ylab('Bicep Girth') + ggtitle("Sex and the Relationship between Thigh Girth and Bicep Girth") + guides(color=guide_legend("Sex"))
p
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

sex_bdims <- sex_bdims %>%
  mutate(bithi_ratio = bic_gi/thi_gi)

p2=boxplot(sex_bdims$bithi_ratio ~ sex_bdims$sex_categorical, col="blue", main="Bicep/Thigh Girth Ratios in Men and Women", ylab="Bicep/Thigh Girth Ratio", xlab="Sex")

sex_bdims %>%
  group_by(sex_categorical) %>%

QUESTION 2: Limitations: A limitation of this EDA is the extent of the data set. Due to a limited number of observations, we will not be able to compare shoulder girths of men and women of the exact same weights (ex. compare the average shoulder girth of men and women, both whom weigh 65 kilograms), but rather had to compare shoulder girths between men and women that fall in the same weight ranges. So, we conducted our initial exploratory data analysis on three different weight ranges–which is as close to considering exact weights as we can in our research. The data ranges for weight we use are (1) 60-70 kilograms, (2) 70-80 kilograms, and (3) 80-90 kilograms.

60-70 RANGE Discussion: The first two summary statistics we analyzed are average shoulder girth (in centimeters) of males weighing between 60 and 70 kilograms and average shouldger girth for females who weigh between 60 and 70 kilograms. We see that the average shoulder girth is larger than the average of females, by a difference of 9.15 centimeters. Furthermore, our side-by-side boxplot compares the 2 numerical distributions that we are focusing on by providing a visualization of the differences and similarities of our two groups (males and females). The median male shoulder girth is higher than the median female shoulder girth. The spread and IQR of the two boxplots are roughly the same and both are symmetric. There are no observed outliers in either population. Although we cannot yet say if the observed differences in mean between the males and females is statistically significant, the difference, along with the side-by-side boxplots support that we should further explore our research question and that there may be some validity to our hypothesis.

Conclusion: When considering the EDA of each data range and comparing the findings, the general trend for average mean shoulder girth for the same weight range is that males have a higher average than females. It is interesting to note that as the weight range increased, the difference in male average shoulder girth and female average girth decreased. All side-by-side boxplots also showed relatively simialar data across each weight range. These initial findings support our futher analysis of how weight, sex, and shoulder girth may all be related.

QUESTION 3: The ages of women included in this lab were from 18 to 67 years old, which include 2 extra years on either end of the early adult and middle adult cutoff ranges from the research article we found. We found that early adult aged women have a higher proportion of women with waist girths over 39in (0.85769) than the proportion of middle aged women with waist girths above 39in (0.1115). These surprising findings were not in support of our hypothesis and make us want to explore more how body dimensions change as age increases.

Age < 40 and waist girth > 39in: 223/260 = 0.85769 (Early aged women)

Age > 40 and waist girth > 39in: 29/260 = 0.1115 (Middle aged women)
